# CFF Project Memory

## Architecture
- **Dual DB**: cff_api (port 8002) connects to LOCAL postgres (parameters) + REMOTE postgres at 150.241.245.65 (demands, resources, assignments)
- **Solver** (port 8004) calls cff_api via httpx (180s timeout, `solver_v2/api/client.py:32`)
- **NGINX** on server proxies `/dev/ai` → 8002, `/dev/planner` → 8004
- Docker compose: `mock_data_v2/database_application_v2/docker-compose.yml`

## Key Performance Finding (2026-02-09)
- External DB queries are slow (1.5-2.9s for 1 record) due to missing indexes
- `resource_blocks.py:172-175` has CONCAT JOIN (full table scan) — worst offender
- `demands.py:87,92` uses DATE() wrapper preventing index use
- NGINX `/dev/ai` missing proxy timeouts (60s default vs needed 300s)
- Full investigation: `solver_v2/planner_dev/data-fetch.md`
- Diagnostic script: `solver_v2/Planner_test/diagnose_fetch_timeout.py`

## Previous Bugs Fixed
- `service.py:643-694`: Replaced hardcoded two-call strategy (category=blocking/service) with FE-driven single call (category=all). FE's replannable_demand_type is single source of truth. lock_allocations=false → no blocks; true → all block except replannable types.
- `resource_blocks.py`: Added CT Jour de compensation to BLOCKING_CALENDAR_TYPES + TRIM() on all calendar_type comparisons (DB has trailing whitespace on CT values in dev, clean in UAT)
- `data_pipeline.py`: inverted locked_date_ranges (start > end) now skipped with warning
- `data_pipeline.py`: `parse_date()` handles space-separated datetime from API
- `data_processor.py`: `_parse_absence_datetime()` handles API datetime format

## Data Quality Notes
- External DB `assignments.calendar_type` has trailing whitespace on some values (e.g. "CT Jour de compensation ") in DEV only. UAT is clean. TRIM() in SQL handles this.
- Docker compose service name is `api` (not `cff_api`), container name is `cff_api`
- `resource_blocks.py` empty WHERE clause bug: `category=all` + `include_unmatched=True` + no other filters → SQL syntax error (pre-existing, not fixed)

## FE Payload Logic (Single Source of Truth)
- `plan_range` = primary filter, always applied server-side
- `lock_allocations=false` → no blockers at all, solver assigns freely
- `lock_allocations=true` + `replannable_demand_type=[]` → ALL types block
- `lock_allocations=true` + `replannable_demand_type=["X"]` → all block except X
- No hardcoded category lists in solver. API still has BLOCKING/SERVICE lists for debug endpoints.

